+# Design
+
+This package provides a reusable rate-limiting core with two algorithms, two storage backends, a decorator adapter, and ASGI middleware for FastAPI or Starlette. The implementation is intentionally small, but it is structured so that application code uses a single `enforce()` interface regardless of whether the limiter is running in-process or against Redis.
+
+## Overview
+
+The request path is the same for middleware, decorators, and direct library calls:
+
+```mermaid
+flowchart LR
+    A[Incoming request or function call] --> B[Key extraction]
+    B --> C[Limiter enforce(key, cost)]
+    C --> D[Algorithm-specific backend operation]
+    D --> E[Decision]
+    E --> F[Allow and attach headers]
+    E --> G[Deny and emit retry metadata]
+```
+
+The middleware layer turns transport-specific input into a key, delegates enforcement to a limiter, and maps the returned `Decision` into HTTP headers and a `429` response when needed. The decorator does the same mapping for Python callables by raising a typed exception.
+
+## Components
+
+### `Decision`
+
+`Decision` is the normalized output of all enforcement calls:
+
+- `allowed`: whether the request may proceed;
+- `retry_after_ms`: how long until retry is likely to succeed;
+- `remaining`: estimated remaining capacity after the decision;
+- `reset_ts`: epoch milliseconds when the limiter is expected to be fully reset or fully replenished.
+
+A common decision object keeps middleware and decorators algorithm-agnostic.
+
+### Algorithms
+
+#### Token bucket
+
+Token bucket stores a token balance and the last refill timestamp for each key. Every call first refills based on elapsed time, clamps the balance to capacity, and then attempts to spend `cost`. This algorithm is a good default for APIs that want to allow bursts while still constraining average rate.
+
+The implementation uses floating-point token balances so fractional refill between calls is preserved. `retry_after_ms` is based on the deficit divided by refill rate.
+
+#### Sliding-window counter
+
+Sliding-window counter tracks three values per key: current bucket start, current bucket count, and previous bucket count. Effective usage is computed as:
+
+```text
+current_count + previous_count * overlap_weight
+```
+
+where `overlap_weight` shrinks linearly as the current period advances. This approximates a true sliding-window log but keeps state bounded and cheap to update.
+
+The chosen semantics are stronger than fixed windows at bucket boundaries and operationally cheaper than logs in Redis.
+
+## Backends
+
+### In-memory backend
+
+`InMemoryBackend` is used for single-process deployments and tests. It stores key state in Python dictionaries protected by a re-entrant lock. The lock makes compound read-modify-write operations atomic within one process and is sufficient for thread-based concurrency tests. It does not coordinate across processes.
+
+Time handling is split deliberately:
+
+- `time.monotonic()` drives token refill math, protecting against local wall-clock jumps;
+- wall-clock time is used only to produce `reset_ts` values for callers.
+
+### Redis backend
+
+`RedisBackend` is the distributed option. Each algorithm is implemented as a Lua script loaded into Redis. The script performs the entire enforcement flow atomically:
+
+1. read current state for the key;
+2. obtain authoritative server time with `TIME`;
+3. compute refill or sliding-window overlap;
+4. decide allow/deny;
+5. write back updated state and TTL;
+6. return decision fields.
+
+This design prevents lost updates because no two clients can interleave the read and write portions of the same key mutation.
+
+Using Redis server time also gives a single clock domain for all application workers. That matters for `retry_after_ms` and `reset_ts`, especially when hosts have imperfect NTP sync.
+
+## Request flow through middleware
+
+```text
+HTTP request
+  -> key_fn(request)
+  -> limiter.enforce(key)
+  -> backend atomic state transition
+  -> Decision
+     -> allowed: forward request, attach X-RateLimit-* headers
+     -> denied: return 429, attach X-RateLimit-* and Retry-After
+```
+
+Headers emitted:
+
+- `X-RateLimit-Limit`
+- `X-RateLimit-Remaining`
+- `X-RateLimit-Reset`
+- `Retry-After` on denial
+
+The middleware stays thin on purpose. All policy is pushed into the limiter and backend so behavior stays consistent across direct calls, decorators, and HTTP traffic.
+
+## Failure modes
+
+### Redis unavailable
+
+If Redis cannot be reached, the backend will raise. The middleware supports a configurable degradation strategy through `fail_open`:
+
+- `fail_open=True` allows the request through without headers when the limiter infrastructure is unavailable;
+- `fail_open=False` propagates the backend failure so the application can fail closed.
+
+Fail-open is a pragmatic default for user-facing systems where availability matters more than temporary quota enforcement. Fail-closed is appropriate for sensitive endpoints or expensive downstream operations.
+
+### Script cache miss
+
+Redis may forget a previously loaded script after restart or failover. The backend detects `NOSCRIPT`, reloads scripts, and retries transparently.
+
+### Local process restarts
+
+In-memory state disappears on restart. That is acceptable because the backend is explicitly scoped to tests and single-process usage.
+
+### Approximation error in sliding window
+
+The sliding-window counter is not exact. Near bucket boundaries, effective usage is an approximation. The tradeoff is accepted because memory and CPU remain bounded while boundary fairness remains much better than fixed-window counters.
+
+## Degradation strategy
+
+The system is designed so transport adapters do not need special-case logic for algorithm details. When Redis is reachable, the distributed backend provides correct cross-worker enforcement. When Redis is unavailable, applications should choose policy explicitly:
+
+- use `InMemoryBackend` in tests, local development, or intentionally single-process services;
+- use `RedisBackend` in distributed production;
+- configure middleware to fail open or fail closed based on endpoint criticality.
+
+This keeps the package predictable: correctness is strongest when Redis is present, but operational behavior under backend failure is still under application control.
